[[Image:Navy_Strategic_Systems_Programs_logo.jpg|thumb|200px|Logo used by the [[United States Navy|US Navy]] Strategic Systems Programs, which carries out shakedown operations]]
A '''Demonstration and Shakedown Operation (DASO)''' is a series of [[Shakedown (testing)|missile tests]] conducted by the [[United States Navy]] and the [[Royal Navy]].<ref name = "www.uscs.org">{{cite web | url = http://www.uscs.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/DS05_Sumarine-Missile-Firings.pdf | title = SUBMARINE MISSILE FIRINGS | date = | accessdate = 27 November 2017 }}</ref> These tests are employed to validate a [[weapon system]] [[Submarine-launched ballistic missile|(SLBM)]] and ensure a submarine crew's readiness to use that system. A shakedown operation usually occurs after a [[refueling and overhaul]] process or construction of a new submarine. Testing of missile systems allows collection of flight-data, and examinations of submarine launch platforms.<ref name = "www.lockheedmartin.co.uk">{{cite web | url = https://www.lockheedmartin.co.uk/us/news/press-releases/2016/september/ssc-space-trdent.html | title = Successful Trident II D5 Missile Flight Test Supports Navy Submarine Certification for Strategic Patrol | date = | accessdate = 27 November 2017 }}</ref>

The first DASO test occurred July 20, 1960 on the [[USS George Washington (SSBN-598)|USS George Washington]], using the [[UGM-27 Polaris#Polaris A-1|Polaris A-1]]. Modern tests use the [[UGM-133 Trident II]], launching from an [[Ohio-class submarine]].<ref name = "www.jhuapl.edu">{{cite web | url = http://www.jhuapl.edu/techdigest/TD/td2904/Gibsonl.pdf | title = The Fleet Ballistic Missile Strategic Weapon System: APL’s Efforts for the U.S. Navy’s Strategic Deterrent System and the Relevance to Systems Engineering | date = | accessdate = 27 November 2017 }}</ref>

